<p><i><b>Looking Backward: 2000-1887</b></i> is a <a href="/wiki/Utopia" title="Utopia">utopian</a> novel by <a href="/wiki/Edward_Bellamy" title="Edward Bellamy">Edward Bellamy</a>, a lawyer and writer from <a href="/wiki/Western_Massachusetts" title="Western Massachusetts">Western Massachusetts</a>, and was first published in <a href="/wiki/1888_in_literature" title="1888 in literature">1888</a>. According to <a href="/wiki/Erich_Fromm" title="Erich Fromm">Erich Fromm</a>, <i>Looking Backward</i> is "one of the most remarkable books ever published in America."<sup id="cite_ref-qlfjpt_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-qlfjpt-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>It was the third largest bestseller of its time, after <i><a href="/wiki/Uncle_Tom%27s_Cabin" title="Uncle Tom's Cabin">Uncle Tom's Cabin</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/Ben-Hur_(novel)" title="Ben-Hur (novel)" class="mw-redirect">Ben-Hur: A Tale of the Christ</a></i>.<sup id="cite_ref-qlfjpt_0-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-qlfjpt-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> It influenced a large number of intellectuals, and appears by title in many of the major <a href="/wiki/Marxism" title="Marxism">Marxist</a> writings of the day. "It is one of the few books ever published that created almost immediately on its appearance a political mass movement."<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> Several "Bellamy Clubs" sprang up all over the United States for discussing and propagating the book's ideas. This political movement came to be known as Nationalism.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> The novel also inspired several <a href="/wiki/Commune_(intentional_community)" title="Commune (intentional community)">utopian communities</a>.</p>
